				https://keyassets.timeincuk.net/inspirewp/live/wp-content/uploads/sites/34/2023/03/bordeaux-grapes-vines-alamy-E7AK2F-620x410.jpg 620w,
				https://keyassets.timeincuk.net/inspirewp/live/wp-content/uploads/sites/34/2023/03/bordeaux-grapes-vines-alamy-E7AK2F-920x609.jpg 920w,
				https://keyassets.timeincuk.net/inspirewp/live/wp-content/uploads/sites/34/2023/03/bordeaux-grapes-vines-alamy-E7AK2F-1220x807.jpg 1220w,
			"/>	</figure>
			<figcaption class="wp-caption-text">
			
			Credit: Nick Maslen / Alamy Stock Photo		</figcaption>
	</div>
	</div>
									
							
				<div class="post-body">
						
					<div class="articleBody">
														<div class="post-tags icon-tags">
		<ul>
							<li><a href="https://www.decanter.com/tag/highlights/" class="post-tags-item" rel="tag" name="Highlights">Highlights</a></li>
							<li><a href="https://www.decanter.com/tag/news-home/" class="post-tags-item" rel="tag" name="News Home">News Home</a></li>
					</ul>
	</div>
																			
																									
																																		
													<p>Bordeauxâs wine bureau, the CIVB, confirmed a financing deal has been agreed with the government to help winemakers pull up thousands of hectares of vineyards, as announced at the <em>Salon d&#8217;Agriculture</em> show in Paris.</p>
<p>âThese tools put us in a position to pull out 9,500 hectares of vines in [the department of] Gironde,â the CIVB said. <strong><a href="https://www.decanter.com/wine/wine-regions/bordeaux-wines/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">Bordeaux</a></strong>&#8216;s wine region had around 108,000 hectares of vines in 2022, according to figures from the wine bureau.</p>
<p><div class="ad-container ad-container--mobile"><div id="post-inline-1" class="ipc-advert"></div></div></p>
<p>The CIVB had previously argued that uprooting approximately 10% the region&#8217;s vines could help cut oversupply, which is partly due to falling consumer demand.</p>
<p>Total financing of â¬57m (Â£50.6m) is set to be made available for a âsanitary&#8217; grubbing up scheme, said the CIVB.</p>
<p>The French government is set to provide â¬38m, of which â¬30m is already confirmed, the CIVB said. Another â¬19m of financing will then be provided by the CIVB, subject to approval by the interprofessional bodyâs board.</p>
<p><div class="ad-container ad-container--mobile"><div id="post-inline-2" class="ipc-advert"></div></div></p>
<p>It follows months of discussions between Franceâs agriculture minister, Marc Fesneau, the president of the Nouvelle Aquitaine region, Alain Rousset, and the president and vice-president of the CIVB, Allan Sichel and Bernard Farges respectively.</p>
<p>While the CIVB has said it is confident in the future and in winemakers&#8217; ability to adapt, it believes grubbing around 10% of the region&#8217;s vines could help put production on a more sustainable footing.</p>
<p>âWe estimate that weâre facing annual overproduction of 300,000hl [40m bottles], to which must be added 200,000hl sold at unremunerative prices,â Sichel told the CIVB&#8217;s general assembly last December.</p>
<div class="ad-container ad-container--mobile"><div id="post-inline-3" class="ipc-advert"></div></div>
<div class="injection"></div>
<p>Last month, Girondeâs chamber of agriculture said that one third of the regionâs wine growers were facing economic difficulty, based on a recent survey. It said many of those in difficulty wished to continue in wine, but some desired to leave the sector.</p>
<p>News of the grubbing up scheme deal comes after Franceâs government recently announced <strong><a href="https://www.decanter.com/wine-news/french-government-floats-e160m-fund-to-ease-wine-crisis-497209/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">a â¬160m funding plan to distil excess wine across the country</a></strong> into industrial alcohol to help deal with a short-term &#8216;crisis in the wine sector&#8217;.</p>
<hr>
